Kids.Text: Unified Assurance and Analytics: Protected Services - Handbook

elements.Text: A protected service is a group of a set of services that can protect each other (such as HA feature) or can share the network load within themselves. The protected service contains a circuit or path that traverses one or more nodes. When a service becomes inactive the other services can take over active service to ensure continuity of the network.
This document describes protected service in Unified Assurance and Analytics (UAA), how to create the service and he types of protected services.
The requirements for the Protected Services are as follows:

Kids.Text: For Trail and SNC Protected Services, UAA version 22.12 or higher is required.
For RING protection, UAA version 23.04 or higher is required.

elements.Text: As Protected service is not a service in itself but is group of services that provide a protection strategy.
The assumptions for Unified Assurance and Analytics Protected Services are:

Kids.Text: Protected service does not have endpoints.
Performance collection is not be done on a protected service.

elements.Text: Ring Protected Services helps in implementing G803.2 rings as part of the Ethernet Assurance. A Protected services cannot be created via UI. It can be created only via swagger UI / import with type RING, G8302_RING. Included services can be either a service, connection, or another protected service.
The ring protected service must meet the following requirements:

Kids.Text: It implements the ring protection strategy.
It considers all the available paths in a ring, while performing SIA. If a ring is part of a service and if one of the segments of that ring is unavailable, then:
if there is no alternate path from entry to exit of that ring.
If there is one possible path from entry to exit of that ring, service becomes

elements.Text: In the following image, if there is a fault between C and D device in the ring, then the service takes the other path.
If there is a fault, then the service impacted are only the ones on Device D.
No entry and exit points for Ring protection. Service can enter/exit from any node in a ring.

Kids.Text: The ring will be added as a protected service and is stored under the protected_service table with the type
All the services/connections that are part of ring will be stored under

elements.Text: Where rings and normal services/ connections are segments of Parent/ Main service,
Parent service availability will be set to UNAVAILABLE, if,
Case A: Atleast one of immediate segment services (both ring and non-ring) is UNAVAILABLE
Case B: No path is found between source and destination nodes of a parent service.
Parent service availability will be set to AT_RISK, if,
Case A: Atleast one of non-ring segment services is AT_RISK and atleast one path is found between source and destination nodes of a parent service.

Case B: If all non-ring segments are AVAILABLE and atleast one of the included services of ring segment is UNAVAILABLE and atleast one path is found between source and destination Nodes of a Parent Service.
Parent service availability will be AVAILABLE, if,
All of the non ring segments are AVAILABLE and all ring segments are AVAILABLE.

Kids.Text: AT_RISK & AVAILABLE will not be considered for RING availability
Possible availability states for RING are UNKNOWN AND UNAVAILABLE
All the included services are UNAVAILABLE OR
Atleast one of the included sub-ring of type G8032_RING is UNAVAILABLE
When RING is not UNAVAILABLE it will be UNKNOWN.

elements.Text: Currently, the protected services can only be created using Swagger API or Import/Export (Refer import and export guide for help) of services.
There could be more than 1 active service between the endpoints/nodes.

Kids.Text: The scope of improvement under the topology is to implement Protection switching, Active or Standby, whichever applicable,
for services and connections. It also helps in defining the endpoints for a service or a connection.

A single service or a connection can be formed either by single direct path connecting both sides trail endpoints ie.(source and destination points), or with a group of intermediate services which is a segment between the trail endpoints. A particular service/ connection can have multiple paths.
, the service_id will be updated on the corresponding endpoint in the end_point table (i.e., endpoint-to-service is a many-to-one relation) and also in network_connection_end_point table.

, the connection_id and associated endpoint_id will be stored in intermediate relational table (network-connection_end_point) between NetworkConnection and EndPoint (i.e., network connectiion-to-end point relation is many-to-many).
